1
00:00:02,368 --> 00:00:04,301
So, tell me about your day—
how's it going

2
00:00:04,303 --> 00:00:05,535
with the particle detector?

3
00:00:05,537 --> 00:00:07,838
Wow! You remember that?

4
00:00:07,840 --> 00:00:09,506
Yeah, I listen
to what you say.

5
00:00:09,508 --> 00:00:11,041
You're building
a particle detector

6
00:00:11,043 --> 00:00:12,876
using superfluid helium.

7
00:00:12,878 --> 00:00:14,878
You know, when you
talk like that,

8
00:00:14,880 --> 00:00:17,381
I want to take you
right here on this table.

9
00:00:17,383 --> 00:00:19,383
And you know
from past experience

10
00:00:19,385 --> 00:00:21,285
this table cannot support
both our weight.

11
00:00:23,021 --> 00:00:24,721
So, how's
the detector going?

12
00:00:24,723 --> 00:00:27,057
Well, it's tricky working
with superfluids.

13
00:00:27,059 --> 00:00:28,292
Whatever container
you put them in,

14
00:00:28,294 --> 00:00:29,693
they kind of
creep up the sides

15
00:00:29,695 --> 00:00:31,194
and crawl out
all on their own.

16
00:00:31,196 --> 00:00:33,597
Kind of like
Sheldon's ant farm.

17
00:00:33,599 --> 00:00:36,266
Exactly, except you don't have
a lunatic running around,

18
00:00:36,268 --> 00:00:39,670
yelling, "I fed you sugar water,
why are you biting me?"

19
00:00:41,306 --> 00:00:43,373
Come on, this is boring— you
really want to talk about this?

20
00:00:43,375 --> 00:00:44,308
No, I do.

21
00:00:44,310 --> 00:00:45,676
I-I didn't write
"superfluid helium"

22
00:00:45,678 --> 00:00:47,477
on this napkin for nothing.

23
00:00:48,313 --> 00:00:49,613
Okay, well...

24
00:00:49,615 --> 00:00:50,981
This is cool.

25
00:00:50,983 --> 00:00:53,317
Uh, there's a thing called
"superfluid vacuum theory",

26
00:00:53,319 --> 00:00:55,319
where empty space is
imagined as a superfluid

27
00:00:55,321 --> 00:00:56,887
with all of
its qualities—

28
00:00:56,889 --> 00:00:59,156
viscosity, density,
surface tension...

29
00:01:01,225 --> 00:01:03,593
Hey, if you're pausing
for dramatic effect,

30
00:01:03,595 --> 00:01:05,929
I'd keep it moving.

31
00:01:05,931 --> 00:01:07,431
No, no.

32
00:01:09,500 --> 00:01:12,869
People don't talk
about surface tension.

33
00:01:12,871 --> 00:01:16,239
If you imagine our
three-space as the surface

34
00:01:16,241 --> 00:01:18,942
of an N-dimensional
superfluid bubble...

35
00:01:18,944 --> 00:01:22,045
This... is exciting.

36
00:01:22,047 --> 00:01:23,280
This is really exciting.

37
00:01:23,282 --> 00:01:24,414
I have to go
find Sheldon.

38
00:01:24,416 --> 00:01:27,484
Okay, well,
if you find him,

39
00:01:27,486 --> 00:01:28,719
use the kitchen island—

40
00:01:28,721 --> 00:01:30,654
that coffee table will not
support both of you.

41
00:01:33,624 --> 00:01:36,426
