Click the
mouse with me.

115
00:05:03,870 --> 00:05:05,871
One...

116
00:05:05,873 --> 00:05:07,373
two...

117
00:05:07,375 --> 00:05:08,607
three...

118
00:05:08,609 --> 00:05:10,209
Click.

119
00:05:13,546 --> 00:05:14,680
Well, we did it.

120
00:05:14,682 --> 00:05:16,715
Yes, we did,
my friend.

121
00:05:16,717 --> 00:05:17,850
Is your tongue blue?

122
00:05:17,852 --> 00:05:20,753
I don't want to
talk about it.

123
00:05:21,855 --> 00:05:23,655
Okay, movie night—
what do you want to watch?

124
00:05:23,657 --> 00:05:25,657
Whatever happened
to that ape movie you were in?

125
00:05:25,659 --> 00:05:26,792
Oh, God.

126
00:05:26,794 --> 00:05:27,926
Probably nothing.

127
00:05:27,928 --> 00:05:29,862
I think I saw the director
twirling a sign

128
00:05:29,864 --> 00:05:31,997
outside the Verizon store.

129
00:05:31,999 --> 00:05:33,365
Search for it.

130
00:05:33,367 --> 00:05:34,400
Wha... no.

131
00:05:34,402 --> 00:05:35,367
No! Why?

132
00:05:35,369 --> 00:05:36,668
'Cause it would be
fun to watch.

133
00:05:36,670 --> 00:05:38,237
It would be humiliating.

134
00:05:38,239 --> 00:05:40,806
Well, now we have
two reasons.

135
00:05:42,575 --> 00:05:43,575
They have it.

136
00:05:43,577 --> 00:05:44,543
Please,
can we watch it?

137
00:05:44,545 --> 00:05:45,677
Please?

138
00:05:45,679 --> 00:05:48,080
Fine, but I'm telling you—
it's terrible.

139
00:05:48,082 --> 00:05:50,482
Have you even seen it?
No.

140
00:05:50,484 --> 00:05:52,017
Well, maybe it turned out
better than you think.

141
00:05:53,187 --> 00:05:55,087
Bananas,
get your fresh bananas.

142
00:05:55,889 --> 00:05:57,923
It really didn't.

143
00:06:02,695 --> 00:06:06,331
Sheldon, this is
superfluid helium.

144
00:06:06,333 --> 00:06:07,699
Put this in
your mouth,

145
00:06:07,701 --> 00:06:09,601
your tongue will
freeze and break off.

146
00:06:11,337 --> 00:06:14,173
Does it smell like blueberries?

147
00:06:14,175 --> 00:06:15,175
No.

148
00:06:15,176 --> 00:06:17,242
Then we're probably okay.

149
00:06:17,244 --> 00:06:19,178
Hey, your paper
got mentioned

150
00:06:19,180 --> 00:06:20,679
on the Quantum Diaries
physics blog.

151
00:06:20,681 --> 00:06:21,914
Really?

152
00:06:21,916 --> 00:06:23,582
Wh-What'd they say?

153
00:06:23,584 --> 00:06:25,250
Uh, it's basically
a summary of the theory,

154
00:06:25,252 --> 00:06:26,952
but there's a bunch of positive
comments on the message board.

155
00:06:26,954 --> 00:06:29,288
Let me see,
let me see.

156
00:06:29,290 --> 00:06:32,658
One calls it "insightful
and innovative".

157
00:06:32,660 --> 00:06:34,493
We're insightful
and innovative.

158
00:06:34,495 --> 00:06:37,029
Ooh, nice to meet you,
Mr. Insightful.

159
00:06:37,031 --> 00:06:39,131
Oh, the pleasure is mine,
Mr. Innovative.

160
00:06:40,767 --> 00:06:42,768
Uh, another one says,
"The concept shows

161
00:06:42,770 --> 00:06:44,770
some real out-of-the-box
thinking".

162
00:06:44,772 --> 00:06:47,339
Do you hear that,
Mr. Out-Of-The?

163
00:06:47,341 --> 00:06:50,542
I do, indeed,
Mr. Box-Thinking.

164
00:06:50,544 --> 00:06:51,844
How are you today,

165
00:06:51,846 --> 00:06:54,713
Mr. Can-You-Believe-
These-Jack-Asses?

166
00:06:54,715 --> 00:06:57,015
Just dandy, Mr...

167
00:06:57,017 --> 00:07:00,652
I-Wish-I-Was-
Better-At-Improv.

168
00:07:00,654 --> 00:07:02,821
Read another one.
Okay, okay. Uh...

169
00:07:02,823 --> 00:07:05,357
"The analogy
between space-time

170
00:07:05,359 --> 00:07:08,627
and a supercooled fluid is
either meaningless or... false".

171
00:07:08,629 --> 00:07:12,464
"I wish this blog would
devote itself to real science

172
00:07:12,466 --> 00:07:14,733
"instead of wasting
our time with crackpot,

173
00:07:14,735 --> 00:07:17,870
wannabe theoreticians
in a rush to publish".

174
00:07:17,872 --> 00:07:19,004
Who wrote that?

175
00:07:19,006 --> 00:07:20,305
It's anonymous,

176
00:07:20,307 --> 00:07:23,142
and user name
"General Relativity."

177
00:07:23,144 --> 00:07:25,677
Well... I'm responding to it.

178
00:07:25,679 --> 00:07:27,379
Uh, don't lower yourself
to their level.

179
00:07:27,381 --> 00:07:28,814
Look, I am simply

180
00:07:28,816 --> 00:07:31,350
going to defend our work,
scientist to scientist.

181
00:07:31,352 --> 00:07:32,885
And failing that,

182
00:07:32,887 --> 00:07:34,686
suggest that his mother enjoys
a string

183
00:07:34,688 --> 00:07:37,623
of both human
and non-human lovers.

184
00:07:37,625 --> 00:07:40,826
Sheldon, my name's
on that paper, too.

185
00:07:40,828 --> 00:07:42,394
There's no upside to doing this.

186
00:07:42,396 --> 00:07:43,795
He just left another comment.

187
00:07:43,797 --> 00:07:45,664
What does it say?

188
00:07:45,666 --> 00:07:48,867
"Upon review, I've
changed my mind about

189
00:07:48,869 --> 00:07:50,269
"the Cooper-Hofstadter
hypothesis

190
00:07:50,271 --> 00:07:52,671
"that space-time is like
a superfluid. In fact,

191
00:07:52,673 --> 00:07:55,974
"it's inspired me to come up
with my own theory.

192
00:07:55,976 --> 00:07:57,843
"Maybe space-time is like
two clowns

193
00:07:57,845 --> 00:07:59,144
"with their heads in a bucket,

194
00:07:59,146 --> 00:08:03,115
much like Cooper
and Hofstadter."

195
00:08:03,117 --> 00:08:04,850
Can I respond now?

196
00:08:04,852 --> 00:08:06,485
Do it.

197
00:08:06,487 --> 00:08:09,855
You mess with the bull,
you get the horns.

198
00:08:09,857 --> 00:08:13,425
I'm about to show this guy
just how horny I can be.

199
00:08:17,897 --> 00:08:20,065
Somebody else do it.

200
00:08:22,068 --> 00:08:24,236
Doctor, please help me.

201
00:08:24,238 --> 00:08:28,073
I think I might be turning
into a killer gorilla.

202
00:08:28,075 --> 00:08:30,876
Why do you think you're turning
into a killer gorilla

203
00:08:30,878 --> 00:08:32,578
and not just a regular gorilla?

204
00:08:32,580 --> 00:08:36,181
